  "local_port": 50478,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Is there an Android application that I can use to lookup words anywhere on my phone, without needing to have the application opened?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several Android applications designed to let you look up words anywhere on your device without needing to manually open the app each time. These apps typically integrate seamlessly with your system, allowing quick access through text selection, floating widgets, or shortcuts. Here are some popular options:\n\n### 1. **Google Translate**\nWhile primarily a translation tool, Google Translate offers robust dictionary features. It can be accessed via:\n\n- **Tap to Translate**: This feature allows you to copy text in any app, and a Google Translate bubble will appear for instant translation or definition without switching apps.\n  \n  **How to Enable:**\n  - Open Google Translate.\n  - Tap on the three-line menu (\u2261) and select **Settings**.\n  - Enable **Tap to Translate** and follow the on-screen instructions.\n\n### 2. **The Free Dictionary by Farlex**\nThis app provides comprehensive definitions, synonyms, and translations. It offers convenient access methods:\n\n- **Text Selection Integration**: After selecting a word in any app, you can choose to look it up in The Free Dictionary from the context menu.\n- **Widget Support**: You can add a dictionary widget to your home screen for quick access.\n\n  **How to Use:**\n  - Install and open The Free Dictionary.\n  - Grant necessary permissions for text selection integration.\n  - Select a word in any app, tap the share or context menu, and choose The Free Dictionary to see the definition instantly.\n\n### 3. **WordWeb Dictionary**\nWordWeb is a powerful dictionary and thesaurus app that can be accessed without leaving your current app.\n\n- **Floating Widget**: Allows you to look up words by tapping the widget button on your screen.\n- **Text Selection Integration**: Similar to other dictionary apps, you can look up selected words directly from the text.\n\n  **How to Use:**\n  - Install WordWeb from the Google Play Store.\n  - Enable the floating widget through the app settings.\n  - When you encounter a word you want to define, tap the floating widget and enter the word to get an instant definition.\n\n### 4. **QuickDic**\nQuickDic is specifically designed for quick word lookups across your device.\n\n- **Overlay Feature**: Displays definitions in an overlay window that appears over any app.\n- **Quick Access Shortcut**: Use a dedicated button or gesture to activate the lookup tool instantly.\n\n  **How to Use:**\n  - Download and install QuickDic from the Google Play Store.\n  - Configure the overlay and shortcut settings within the app.\n  - Use the shortcut or gesture while browsing any content to look up words without leaving your current screen.\n\n### 5. **Google Assistant**\nWhile not a dedicated dictionary app, Google Assistant can provide definitions on the fly.\n\n- **Voice Commands**: Simply say, \"Hey Google, define [word]\" to get an immediate definition.\n- **Tap for Assistant**: Highlight a word and tap the Assistant icon to get its definition without typing.\n\n  **How to Use:**\n  - Ensure Google Assistant is enabled on your device.\n  - Use voice commands or the Assistant button to request definitions anytime.\n\n### **Setting Up System-Wide Text Selection Integration**\n\nFor the best experience, ensure that the dictionary app you choose is set up to integrate with Android\u2019s text selection feature:\n\n1. **Install Your Preferred Dictionary App** from the Google Play Store.\n2. **Open the App and Navigate to Settings**: Look for options like \"Enable Text Selection Integration,\" \"Overlay,\" or \"Floating Widget.\"\n3. **Grant Necessary Permissions**: Allow the app to display over other apps and access text selections.\n4. **Test the Integration**: Select a word in any app, and you should see an option to look it up using your chosen dictionary app.\n\n### **Conclusion**\n\nThese applications offer various ways to quickly look up words across your Android device without the need to constantly open the dictionary app manually. Depending on your specific needs\u2014whether you prefer voice commands, floating widgets, or text selection integration\u2014you can choose the app that best fits your workflow. \n\n**Recommended Apps:**\n- **Google Translate** for translation and definitions with Tap to Translate.\n- **The Free Dictionary by Farlex** for comprehensive definitions and easy integration.\n- **WordWeb Dictionary** for powerful lookup features with a floating widget.\n- **QuickDic** for specialized quick lookup overlays.\n- **Google Assistant** for voice-activated definitions on the go.\n\nFeel free to try out a few to see which one aligns best with your usage preferences!",
